<font color="#FF0000">THE SECOND TIME AROUND</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct 18  0:01:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The second Veteran’s Day anniversary for this site will be upon us in under a month.<br><br>
I thought I would try to go back and recall what I was thinking about myself, the Vietnam War, and my feelings on the observance of Veteran’s Day, this time last year.<br><br>
My words posted on this site from that time portray a Veteran who was ashamed of his Vietnam service, had overriding guilt and fear, felt rejection and discrimination, had strong trust issues, and was very, very, angry. I see a Vietnam Veteran who was just beginning to learn that he was acting out his anger and his flashbacks to the past in ways that were as destructive socially as were the combat methods he used back in ‘Nam to survive, and help others to survive, too.  The enemy, though, was different, but then again, the same. His life long  profession of preventing harm and death to others was the stage upon which endless replays of time warp flashback loops would act out THE MISSION.  He was just beginning to understand  his PTSD which the medical profession diagnosed, as a truly unrelenting gift of destruction.  The grim reaper was at his back, but there was yet no light to the path being taken. Isolated and alone in a self imposed social exile, the gooks were at times his family, his friends, his associates,  perfect strangers, and really, most of all,  that which he called himself. <br><br>
That Vietnam Veteran often felt it was he who was marked upon The Wall. The Wall, the mark of Cain. The essence of shame, the essence of pride, the essence of himself. <br><br>
I like to think that that Vietnam Veteran of last year is different. I think I am. I am not sure where I am at right now, but it is not completely in that place of the past.  My Brothers of Choice show me there are, at times, other ways that work to handle the challenges from without, and from within, where they really count.  Last year, I had no Brothers of Choice. I did not understand what that was all about. I feel I do now. That is true progress! I have let a few inside, and I trust them.<br><br>
Perhaps next year this Vietnam Veteran will see changes again. I think I can bet on it! I want this to happen.  <br><br>
Peace.<br><br>
Art<br>

